<author><name><![CDATA[tokumaru]]></name></author>
<updated>2008-11-09T11:55:25-07:00</updated>
<published>2008-11-09T11:55:25-07:00</published>
<id>http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=4549&amp;p=39800#p39800</id>
<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=4549&amp;p=39800#p39800"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[Question about mappers and their banks]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=4549&amp;p=39800#p39800"><![CDATA[
And you definitley don't want to put CHR data in a fixed ROM bank. In CHR-RAM boards, once the tiles have been sent to the PPU you don't have to keep them mapped anymore.<br /><br />Large amounts of data in general should be kept separated from code, because they are typically accessed at very predictable times, so you can map them in, use them, and map the next thing.<br /><br />The fixed bank should contain your main program and other pieces of code that are used very often. Swappable banks can contain level maps, music engine and data (since the sound engine is usually called only once per frame), graphic data, code for specific game sections (such as bonus stages which differ from the main gameplay)...<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=95">tokumaru</a> — Sun Nov 09, 2008 11:55 am</p><hr />
]]></content>
